Ordinal categorical Features:

O PhysicalHealth (0, 15, 615, 1630)
O MentalHealth (0, 13, 47, 814, 1521, 2230)
O SleepTime (5, 67, 8, 910, 11)

Look categorical but contain ordering:

O AgeCategory

Why misclassifying a feature is dangerous

  • Adds false mathematical assumptions
  • Destroys ordinal ordering
  • Distorts model learning
    • Linear models wrong coefficients
    • Distance models bad distances
    • Tree models poor splits
  • Produces misleading interpretations

Rule:

Classify features by meaning, not appearance.

9 Missing Value Handling Strategy

Decision Table

Feature Missing Count Missing % Strategy Justification
BMI 1604 9.51% Median Imputation BMI is a continuous variable that can have outliers (very high/low values). Median is robust to outliers and won't be affected by extreme values. In medical data, using median preserves the typical body mass index without being skewed by obesity or underweight extremes. Mean would be distorted by outliers.
SleepTime 504 2.99% Median Imputation Sleep hours is continuous with potential outliers (very long/short sleep). Median provides a robust central tendency. In medical context, median sleep time (typically 7-8 hours) is more representative than mean which could be affected by extreme values.
SkinCancer 1164 6.90% Mode Imputation SkinCancer is binary (Yes/No). Mode imputation replaces missing with the most common category. Since most people don't have skin cancer, this assumes missing values follow the majority pattern, which is medically reasonable. Remove rows would lose 7% of data unnecessarily.
DiffWalking 5 0.03% Mode Imputation Only 5 missing values (negligible). DiffWalking is binary. Mode imputation is safe and preserves data. Removing rows would be acceptable but unnecessary for such minimal missingness.

Why Other Methods Are WRONG:

For BMI and SleepTime:

  • Mean Imputation: WRONG - Would be heavily influenced by outliers (very obese patients, sleep disorders)
  • Mode Imputation: WRONG - These are continuous variables, not categorical. Mode would oversimplify.
  • Remove Rows: WRONG - Would lose 9.5% of data (1604 patients), reducing statistical power

For SkinCancer and DiffWalking:

  • Mean/Median: WRONG - Cannot calculate mean/median for categorical Yes/No data
  • Remove Rows: RISKY - Would lose valuable patient data unnecessarily
  • Leave as-is: WRONG - Most ML algorithms cannot handle missing values

Medical Context Justification:

  1. BMI: Missing BMI might be due to patients not being weighed. Using median assumes missing patients have typical body mass, which is a reasonable medical assumption.

  2. SleepTime: Missing sleep data might be from incomplete surveys. Median sleep (7-8 hrs) represents healthy sleep patterns.

  3. SkinCancer: Missing might indicate "not checked" or "not reported". Since skin cancer is relatively rare, assuming "No" (mode) is medically conservative.

  4. DiffWalking: Very few missing values, mode is safe and preserves data.

In[23]:
# Create a copy for preprocessing
df_processed = df.copy()

# 1. BMI - Median Imputation
bmi_median = df_processed['BMI'].median()
df_processed['BMI'].fillna(bmi_median, inplace=True)
print(f" BMI: Filled {1604} missing values with median = {bmi_median:.2f}")

# 2. SleepTime - Median Imputation
sleep_median = df_processed['SleepTime'].median()
df_processed['SleepTime'].fillna(sleep_median, inplace=True)
print(f" SleepTime: Filled {504} missing values with median = {sleep_median:.1f}")

# 3. SkinCancer - Mode Imputation
skincancer_mode = df_processed['SkinCancer'].mode()[0]
df_processed['SkinCancer'].fillna(skincancer_mode, inplace=True)
print(f" SkinCancer: Filled {1164} missing values with mode = '{skincancer_mode}'")

# 4. DiffWalking - Mode Imputation
diffwalking_mode = df_processed['DiffWalking'].mode()[0]
df_processed['DiffWalking'].fillna(diffwalking_mode, inplace=True)
print(f" DiffWalking: Filled {5} missing values with mode = '{diffwalking_mode}'")

# Verify no missing values remain
print("\n" + "=" * 60)
print(f"Total missing values after imputation: {df_processed.isnull().sum().sum()}")
print(" All missing values handled successfully!")

 DiffWalking: Filled 5 missing values with mode = 'No'

11 Task 11: Encoding Strategy

Critical Type Classification Insights

Features That LOOK Numeric But Should Be Treated As Categorical:

NONE in this dataset - but be aware:

  • PhysicalHealth and MentalHealth are discrete numerical (counts of days)
  • They represent countable quantities, not categories
  • They should be treated as numerical for scaling, not encoded as categorical

Features That LOOK Categorical But Contain Ordering:

  1. AgeCategory ORDINAL

    • Contains clear ordering: 18-24 < 25-29 < ... < 80 or older
    • DANGER: Treating as nominal (One-Hot) loses this ordering!
    • CORRECT: Manual ordinal encoding to preserve age progression

  2. GenHealth ORDINAL

    • Contains health quality ordering: Poor < Fair < Good < Very good < Excellent
    • DANGER: One-Hot encoding treats "Poor" and "Excellent" as equally different from "Fair"
    • CORRECT: Ordinal encoding to preserve health progression

Why Misclassifying a Feature is DANGEROUS:

Example 1: Treating AgeCategory as Nominal (WRONG)

# WRONG: One-Hot Encoding
Age_18-24  Age_25-29  Age_30-34  ...  (13 columns)
    1          0          0       ...
    0          1          0       ...

Problem: Model doesn't understand that 25-29 is "between" 18-24 and 30-34 Result: Model can't learn that heart disease risk increases with age Impact: Poor predictive performance, incorrect medical insights

Example 2: Treating GenHealth as Nominal (WRONG)

# WRONG: One-Hot Encoding
GenHealth_Poor  GenHealth_Fair  GenHealth_Good  ...
       1               0               0        ...

Problem: Model treats "Poor" "Fair" as different as "Poor" "Excellent" Result: Can't learn that health progressively improves Impact: Medical nonsense - loses critical health gradient information

Example 3: Treating PhysicalHealth as Categorical (WRONG)

# WRONG: Treating 0-30 days as 31 separate categories

Problem: Creates 31 features, treats 5 days and 6 days as completely unrelated Result: Model can't understand that more days = worse health Impact: Massive feature explosion, loss of numerical relationship

Summary:

Feature Type Misclassification Risk Correct Treatment
Binary Low Label encode (0/1)
Nominal Categorical Medium One-Hot encode
Ordinal Categorical HIGH Manual ordinal mapping
Numerical (treated as categorical) CRITICAL Keep as numerical, scale

Medical Impact: Wrong classification Model learns wrong patterns Incorrect diagnoses Patient harm

Complete Encoding Strategy Table

# Feature Type Encoding Method Why This Method? Why Others Are RISKY?
1 HeartDisease Binary Label Encoding (Yes=1, No=0) Only 2 values, simple 0/1 encoding preserves information without dimensionality increase One-Hot: Creates 2 columns for binary data (redundant, wastes memory)
2 Smoking Binary Label Encoding (Yes=1, No=0) Only 2 values, efficient memory usage, ML models handle 0/1 well One-Hot: Unnecessary for binary, creates multicollinearity
3 AlcoholDrinking Binary Label Encoding (Yes=1, No=0) Only 2 values, maintains simplicity One-Hot: Redundant for binary variables
4 Stroke Binary Label Encoding (Yes=1, No=0) Only 2 values, preserves binary relationship One-Hot: Inefficient for 2 categories
5 DiffWalking Binary Label Encoding (Yes=1, No=0) Only 2 values, simple encoding One-Hot: Overkill for binary feature
6 Sex Binary Label Encoding (Male=1, Female=0) Only 2 values, traditional encoding One-Hot: Not needed for binary
7 PhysicalActivity Binary Label Encoding (Yes=1, No=0) Only 2 values, straightforward One-Hot: Creates unnecessary column
8 Asthma Binary Label Encoding (Yes=1, No=0) Only 2 values, consistent with other binary One-Hot: Inefficient
9 KidneyDisease Binary Label Encoding (Yes=1, No=0) Only 2 values, maintains consistency One-Hot: Wastes dimension
10 SkinCancer Binary Label Encoding (Yes=1, No=0) Only 2 values, simple and effective One-Hot: Not necessary
11 AgeCategory Ordinal Manual Ordinal Encoding (18-24=1, 25-29=2, ... 80+=13) HAS NATURAL ORDER (age increases), preserves progression, model learns age gradient One-Hot: Loses age ordering (treats 18-24 and 80+ as equally different from 40-44)
Label: Would assign arbitrary order
12 GenHealth Ordinal Manual Ordinal Encoding (Poor=1, Fair=2, Good=3, Very good=4, Excellent=5) HAS NATURAL ORDER (health quality increases), model can learn health improves One-Hot: Loses health progression (treats Poor and Excellent as unrelated)
Label: Random order destroys meaning
13 Race Nominal One-Hot Encoding (creates Race_White, Race_Black, etc.) NO NATURAL ORDER between races, one-hot treats all categories equally, no false hierarchy Label: Creates false ordering (White=0, Black=1, Asian=2) - medically wrong
Ordinal: Implies some races are "better" - ethical violation
14 Diabetic Nominal One-Hot Encoding (creates 4 binary columns) NO NATURAL ORDER (4 unrelated categories), each diabetes status is distinct Label: False ordering ("No" < "Yes" < "Borderline" makes no medical sense)
Ordinal: Diabetes types aren't ordered

Critical Justifications:

Why Manual Ordinal Encoding for AgeCategory?

age_mapping = {
    '18-24': 1, '25-29': 2, '30-34': 3, '35-39': 4,
    '40-44': 5, '45-49': 6, '50-54': 7, '55-59': 8,
    '60-64': 9, '65-69': 10, '70-74': 11, '75-79': 12,
    '80 or older': 13
}

Preserves medical knowledge: Heart disease risk with age Model can learn: Higher numbers = older = higher risk One-Hot would: Treat all ages as unrelated can't learn age trend

Why Manual Ordinal Encoding for GenHealth?

health_mapping = {
    'Poor': 1,
    'Fair': 2,
    'Good': 3,
    'Very good': 4,
    'Excellent': 5
}

Preserves health gradient: Better health = higher number Medical logic: Model learns poor health higher heart disease risk One-Hot would: 5 separate columns, loses health progression

Why One-Hot Encoding for Race?

NO ordering exists: White, Black, Asian, Hispanic are categories without hierarchy Ethical: Doesn't imply any race is "better" or "higher" Medical fairness: Each race gets equal treatment in model Label encoding DANGER: Would create racist ordering (Race_0, Race_1, Race_2...)

Why One-Hot Encoding for Diabetic?

4 distinct types: "Yes", "No", "Borderline", "During pregnancy" are unrelated No progression: Borderline "between" Yes and No Pregnancy diabetes: Completely different medical condition Label/Ordinal DANGER: Would create false medical relationships

# ========== 1. LABEL ENCODING FOR BINARY FEATURES ==========
print("\n1 LABEL ENCODING - Binary Features (10 features)")
print("-" * 80)

binary_features = [
    'HeartDisease', 'Smoking', 'AlcoholDrinking', 'Stroke',
    'DiffWalking', 'Sex', 'PhysicalActivity',
    'Asthma', 'KidneyDisease', 'SkinCancer'
]

# Define mappings for binary features
binary_mappings = {
    'HeartDisease': {'No': 0, 'Yes': 1},
    'Smoking': {'No': 0, 'Yes': 1},
    'AlcoholDrinking': {'No': 0, 'Yes': 1},
    'Stroke': {'No': 0, 'Yes': 1},
    'DiffWalking': {'No': 0, 'Yes': 1},
    'Sex': {'Female': 0, 'Male': 1},
    'PhysicalActivity': {'No': 0, 'Yes': 1},
    'Asthma': {'No': 0, 'Yes': 1},
    'KidneyDisease': {'No': 0, 'Yes': 1},
    'SkinCancer': {'No': 0, 'Yes': 1}
}

for feature in binary_features:
    df_encoded[feature] = df_encoded[feature].map(binary_mappings[feature])
    print(f" {feature}: Encoded as 0/1")

print(f"\n Total: {len(binary_features)} binary features encoded")

# ========== 2. MANUAL ORDINAL ENCODING ==========

12 Data Splitting Class Distribution Challenge

Selected choice: Stratified Split

Why this guarantees the requirement

  • Preserves the class distribution of HeartDisease
  • Ensures both Yes and No appear in train and test

Why other methods may fail

  • Random split: minority class may end up only in train or test
  • K-Fold (non-stratified): some folds may miss rare classes

# Compute correlation with target
corr_with_target = df_encoded.corr(numeric_only=True)['HeartDisease']

# Set threshold
threshold = 0.03

# Identify unimportant features
low_corr_features = corr_with_target[
    corr_with_target.abs() < threshold
].index.tolist()

# Remove target if present
low_corr_features = [c for c in low_corr_features if c != 'HeartDisease']

# Drop low-importance features
df_reduced = df_encoded.drop(columns=low_corr_features)

print("Removed features:")
print(low_corr_features)

print(df_reduced.columns.tolist())

13 Data Leakage Awareness

Correct order

  1. Splitting
  2. Encoding
  3. Scaling

Orders that cause data leakage

  • Encoding before splitting
  • Scaling before splitting

Why

  • Encoder/scaler learns statistics from test data
  • Model indirectly sees unseen data

Why leakage is especially dangerous in healthcare ML

  • Inflates accuracy and AUC
  • Creates false clinical confidence
  • Can lead to unsafe medical decisions

14 Scaling Strategy

Chosen scaler: RobustScaler

Justification

  • Outliers

    • BMI and health-day counts contain extreme values
    • RobustScaler uses median and IQR resistant to outliers

  • Medical meaning

    • Preserves relative differences without forcing min/max bounds
    • Avoids distortion from abnormal clinical cases

  • Model sensitivity

    • Suitable for linear, distance-based, and neural models
    • More stable than StandardScaler with skewed health data

Should encoded categorical features be scaled?

No, Why:

  • Scaling destroys categorical meaning
  • Breaks ordinal relationships
  • Encoded values are labels, not measurements

15 Final Pipeline Construction

Chosen approach: Pipeline

Justification

  • Prevents data leakage by enforcing correct order
  • Ensures consistent preprocessing during training and inference
  • Safe for cross-validation and hyperparameter tuning
  • Cleaner, reproducible, and production-ready

Why not others

  • Manual preprocessing: error-prone, easy to leak data
  • ColumnTransformer alone: handles columns, but Pipeline controls the full workflow

Rule

In healthcare ML, always use a Pipeline to guarantee safety and validity.

In[38]:
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from sklearn.preprocessing import RobustScaler
from sklearn.linear_model import LogisticRegression

X = df_reduced.drop(columns=['HeartDisease'])
y = df_reduced['HeartDisease']

pipeline = Pipeline(steps=[
    ('model', LogisticRegression(max_iter=1000))
])

pipeline.fit(X_train, y_train)

print("Train score:", pipeline.score(X_train, y_train))
print("Test score:", pipeline.score(X_test, y_test))

Heart Disease Prediction Using Logistic Regression

1. Problem Overview

The objective of this project is to predict whether an individual has heart disease based on health, lifestyle, and demographic features.

This is a binary classification problem:

  • 0 No heart disease
  • 1 Heart disease

2. Dataset Description

The dataset contains 16,859 records with 26 features, including numerical, binary, and categorical health indicators.

Feature Types

Numerical features

  • BMI
  • PhysicalHealth
  • ~MentalHealth~ (removed)
  • ~SleepTime~ (removed)

Categorical / binary features (already encoded)

  • Smoking, AlcoholDrinking, Stroke
  • PhysicalActivity, GenHealth
  • Asthma, KidneyDisease, SkinCancer
  • One-hot encoded race features (Race_White, Race_Black, etc.)
  • One-hot encoded diabetes status (Diabetic_Yes, Diabetic_No, etc.)

Target variable

  • HeartDisease

3. Data Splitting Strategy

The data was split into:

  • 80% Training set
  • 20% Testing set

A stratified split was applied to preserve the original distribution of heart disease cases in both training and testing datasets.

This ensures a fair and reliable evaluation of model performance.

4. Model Selection

We used Logistic Regression, a widely used and interpretable algorithm for binary classification problems.

Why Logistic Regression?

  • Suitable for binary outcomes
  • Computationally efficient
  • Produces probabilistic outputs
  • Commonly used in healthcare risk prediction

5. Preprocessing and Pipeline

Since all categorical features were already encoded, no additional encoding was applied.

Preprocessing steps:

  • RobustScaler was used to scale numerical features and reduce the influence of outliers
  • Binary and boolean features were passed directly to the model

All steps were combined using a Pipeline to prevent data leakage and ensure reproducibility.

6. Model Performance

The trained model achieved the following accuracy scores: Train score: 0.9023898431665422 Test score: 0.9050179211469535

  • Training Accuracy: 90.24%
  • Testing Accuracy: 90.50%

7. Performance Interpretation

The close similarity between training and testing accuracy indicates:

  • Strong generalization to unseen data
  • No evidence of overfitting
  • Stable and reliable model behavior

The model correctly predicts heart disease status in approximately 9 out of 10 cases.

8. Practical Implications

This model can be used as a baseline clinical decision-support tool, helping to identify individuals at higher risk of heart disease.

Due to its interpretability, Logistic Regression allows for transparent analysis of how different health factors influence predictions.

9. Future Improvements

Possible extensions of this work include:

  • Evaluating ROCAUC and confusion matrix
  • Handling class imbalance using class_weight='balanced'
  • Analyzing feature importance using model coefficients
  • Trying more advanced models (Random Forest, XGBoost)
  • Hyperparameter tuning with GridSearchCV

10. Conclusion

This project demonstrates that careful preprocessing and correct pipeline design can lead to strong predictive performance without complex models.

The Logistic Regression model achieved high accuracy, good generalization, and strong interpretability, making it well-suited for healthcare applications.
